(174, 1, '2015-02-25 21:59:40', '2015-02-25 21:59:40', 'You probably know that doing JavaScript testing is good, but one of the hurdles to overcome is how to test our code on different browsers. Luckily, there are some tools available for helping us overcome this hurdle. One of them is a CLI (<em>command line</em>) named <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/saucie" rel="noreferrer"><em>saucie</em></a> developed by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/igorlima" rel="noreferrer">igorlima</a>. This CLI is a library hosted on <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://www.npmjs.com/" rel="noreferrer">NPM</a>, which allows you to integrate your frontend JavaScript tests with the <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/" rel="noreferrer">SauceLabs</a> platform. SauceLabs makes awesome cross browser testing, and <em>saucie</em> makes it easier to do cross browser testing by CLI.\r\n\r\nA great <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://tobyho.com/2012/06/24/testem-interactive-js-test-runner/" rel="noreferrer">interactive JS Test Runner</a>, the <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem" rel="noreferrer">testem</a> library, uses <em>saucie</em> on its <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem/tree/master/examples/saucelabs" rel="noreferrer">examples</a> and has the following <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://jasmine.github.io/" rel="noreferrer">jasmine</a> sample tests:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>hello.js</em></strong>\r\n<div class="highlight highlight-js">\r\n<pre><span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span> <span class="pl-en" style="color: #795da3;">hello</span>(<span class="pl-vpf">name</span>){\r\n    <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">return</span> “hello “ <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">+</span> (name <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">||</span> ‘world’);\r\n}</pre>\r\n</div>\r\n<strong><em>hello_spec.js</em></strong>\r\n<div class="highlight highlight-js">\r\n<pre>describe(‘hello’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n    it(‘should say hello’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n        expect(hello()).toBe(‘hello world’);\r\n    });\r\n    it(‘should say hello to person’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n        expect(hello(‘Bob’)).toBe(‘hello Bob’);\r\n    });\r\n});</pre>\r\n</div>\r\nRun these tests cross platforms step by step - you need only few command lines, as described below:\r\n<ol class="task-list">\r\n	<li>First of all <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/signup/trial" rel="noreferrer">create your SauceLabs account</a></li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the Sauce credentials are set as <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environment_variable" rel="noreferrer">environment variables</a>:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><strong>SAUCE_USERNAME</strong> - your SauceLabs username</li>\r\n	<li><strong>SAUCE_ACCESS_KEY</strong> - your SauceLabs API/Access key.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>After that set up, follow the scripts below:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>npm install -g testem saucie</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>git clone git@github.com:airportyh/testem.git</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>cd testem/</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>git checkout tags/v0.7.1</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>cd examples/saucelabs/</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Keep that <strong>first</strong> terminal opened, open a <strong>second</strong> terminal, and follow the script below:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>cd testem/examples/saucelabs/</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>testem --port 8080</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Go back to the <strong>first</strong> terminal and type:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="internet explorer" --versionSL="7.0" --platformSL="Windows XP"</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="iphone" --versionSL="8.1" --platformSL="OS X 10.10" --deviceNameSL="iPad Simulator" --deviceOrientationSL="portrait"</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="android" --versionSL="4.1" --platformSL="Linux" --deviceNameSL="Motorola Atrix HD Emulator" --deviceOrientationSL="portrait"</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Note 1:</strong> <em>All platforms are listed <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/platforms/" rel="noreferrer">here</a>. Want to know the values for browserNameSL, versionSL and platformSL params? Check it <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://docs.saucelabs.com/reference/platforms-configurator/#/" rel="noreferrer">here</a></em>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 2:</strong> <em>If you’d like to use the default configuration just type <code>testem ci --port 8080</code> and be happy</em>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 3:</strong> <em>type <code>saucie --help</code> to get a help.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 4:</strong> <em>testem.yml is a <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem#configuration-file" rel="noreferrer">configuration file</a> that specifies which JS framework to use. In this case, we are using JasmineJS.</em>\r\n\r\nDo you feel more comfortable watching a <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://showterm.io/592f4be927803a428035e" rel="noreferrer">video</a> instead? Go ahead and watch <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://showterm.io/592f4be927803a428035e" rel="noreferrer">it</a>.\r\n\r\nJust by typing a few command lines, everything was tested on cross browsers. Now let’s go to SauceLabs and check the result on many browsers, including the mobile ones such as iOS and Android:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/tests/06b62f4bba48469999d7212cf1b62818" rel="noreferrer">iOS test video</a></li>\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/tests/945ebbe3b6044963a017cef5949d1cf6" rel="noreferrer">IE7 test video</a></li>\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/jobs/11bd49cee6cf49d2a76d5b655f6ccb0f" rel="noreferrer">Android test video</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<em>Saucie </em>is still growing up and learning to integrate other platforms like <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://www.browserstack.com/" rel="noreferrer">BrowserStack</a>. New features are coming soon. And these days, it has<a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/igorlima/sauce-js-tests-integration/pull/4" rel="noreferrer"> some improvements</a> from <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach" rel="noreferrer">johanneswuerbach</a>. He made several changes <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach/ember-cli-sauce/commit/27036f2c97454abb5a2065fb5a754e7c972ddad4" rel="noreferrer">to use <em>saucie</em></a> in <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach/ember-cli-sauce" rel="noreferrer">ember-cli-sauce</a>, which is now used by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/tildeio/htmlbars" rel="noreferrer">htmlbars</a>, the rendering engine used by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/emberjs/ember.js" rel="noreferrer">emberjs</a>.\r\n\r\nFeel free to file issue and send pull requests and let’s become <em>saucie</em> even better. Thanks!', 'Getting started with Saucie CLI', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'getting-started-with-saucie-cli', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:12:52', '2015-05-18 17:12:52', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=174', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(175, 1, '2015-02-18 21:58:03', '2015-02-18 21:58:03', '<h2><b>Key Facts</b></h2>\r\n<b>Locations: </b>Corporate HQ in Pittsburgh, PA, and retail stores worldwide\r\n\r\n<b>Industry: </b>Retail - Youth Apparel\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Word </b><b> </b></h2>\r\n<b>From the Project Manager to our UI Developer </b>\r\n<blockquote>I had been fighting for these changes for five months! It was our biggest pain point for our call centers...every day they complain about it. You have saved the day!</blockquote>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The challenge</b></h2>\r\nWhat can be done without an experienced UI team? Not much of anything, really. But Our client needed UI improvements that supported their plans for global expansion, and they had their eyes on the UK and needed their website to truly represent them as a company. The last code written for the website dated back to 2008, with most of it written years before. We stepped in to give them the UI guidance they needed to take their website to the next level. In order for the UI to support their expansion plans, there were serious updates needed to be done for the CSR Application too:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Currency conversion for international business</li>\r\n	<li>Complete website redesign</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>The Journey</b></h2>\r\n<b>Currency conversion for international business</b>\r\n\r\nOur client’s internal e-commerce system only supported currency conversions that either went to or from US dollars. So for those ordering from the UK but using Euros, there was no hope other than to use 3rd party online tools. We designed a module that had the intelligence to call internal API’s to convert the foreign currencies to other foreign currencies without the customer have to worry about using US dollars. This CSR app supports anywhere between 300 or 400 customer representatives at a time, so it needed to be nimble. This module created the workaround by using AJAX, which detected which currency the user was coming from and going to simply by pinging the server, and then created a new, appropriate currency conversion rate based on the information it found on the web.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Complete website redesign</b>\r\n\r\nThere hadn’t been any new UI enhancements added to the website since 2008...and it was obvious. The site needed a serious facelift. It was created in a time when adaptive/responsive design frameworks didn’t exist and IE7 was considered cutting edge - yikes! We dusted the cobwebs off the code, and set to work. For starters, we created a login screen that used modern AJAX &amp; CSS3 for the login screen which communicated errors via animations. Then we created a bulletin board which allowed messages to be left for employees which kept them up to date on news. We integrated social media as well, which helped customer service reps know what was going on in real time, catch any issues before they bubbled over, and gave them insight which created a true sense of empathy. This improved their customer support success and customers were overjoyed.', 'Fortune 1000 Retailer', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'fortune-1000-retailer', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:13:02', '2015-05-18 17:13:02', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=175', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(176, 1, '2015-02-18 21:57:26', '2015-02-18 21:57:26', '<h2>Brazilian beginnings</h2>\r\nI decided to come to the US after working for three years as a consultant after knowing  that I was unhappy with what I was currently doing, and living in a city where you can''t go anywhere without feeling unsafe. The last straw was being mugged while stuck in traffic going home after work.\r\nThat same month I applied for the Toefl Exam (needed for pretty much any school here in the US), and started looking for a program that wouldn''t be too hard to get in and would also add to my resume. One of my co-workers told me about the UC Berkeley Extension course and it sounded like a good option. I did a little bit more research, and decided to take the Project Management Certification Course since it was related to my bachelor’s degree in business, and also added to my work history as a business consultant. After that decision, I had to decide between IDP (International diploma) or ECP (Evening Certificate Program). The main difference is that one is only for international students, and the second one is mainly for people that have a full-time job already, but still want to invest in their education. I disliked the idea of taking a course with people that were only there to study, because I wanted to be around Americans that actually worked,  since it would help me get a real glimpse of what it would be like if I was to live in America. I enjoyed the whole course and made a lot of connections, but when the end of my program was approaching and I was starting to look for an intern position, I realized how hard it was to be from another country while getting companies to give me a chance.\r\n<h2>A foot in the door</h2>\r\nAfter talking to all my teachers, one of them (Introduction to Agile) put me in contact with Amir, but that didn''t work the first time (he was traveling and we stopped exchanging emails after a while). I emailed that teacher again, and this time she put me in contact with Zeo and we scheduled a meeting. I went to the Avenue Code office, and Zeo was pretty straightforward with me. He told me that at that point I couldn''t add any value, but he could put me in contact with Elaine, as she was developing a new project that I would be a good fit for. I had no idea about the whole Cadet Program concept, and met with Elaine without knowing what to expect. I went to one of the client sites to talk to her, and she explained that I could be a unpaid intern and participate in the Code Academy project as a Cadet. I was happy with the opportunity, but I didn''t know how I would tell my parents (who had been sponsoring me while I went to UC Berkeley) that I would like to stay one more year in America without any paycheck. After some discussion and a lot of thinking, I felt that it was a great opportunity and even though my parents said they would not sponsor me anymore, I decided to use my personal savings and invest in myself. Shortly after that, I finished my extension, and went back to Brazil to spend some time with my family and renew my visa.\r\n<h2>On the right track</h2>\r\nI got to Avenue Code by the end of August, and stayed with Avenue Code for the first fifteen days. That was a huge help! During those two weeks, I was going crazy trying to find a place to live. The first day at Avenue Code, Elaine took me to lunch and we chatted a little bit more about what she had planned for me. Since the beginning, she was really open to my suggestions. I believed I should just go with the flow, and eventually it would all make sense. She set two meetings with two different companies, and we agreed that I would work two days in one as a project manager intern, and three days in the other as a scrum master intern. I had no idea what I was going to do in either positions, and I was freaking out about not being able to do a great job, but Elaine always told me to be patient and just be a sponge. The first internship  didn''t work out that well. They were going through some issues with their vendor and also rearranging  their team so I couldn''t help much and felt like I always had to find things to do. The project was so bad that they were considering finding another vendor.\r\n\r\nThe second internship was completely different! I loved it from day one, and my mentor there, Elle, helped me since the beginning and always made sure I was learning something new. Since I do not have a tech background, it was tough finding the rhythm during the first three to four weeks but eventually got easier. Elaine touched base with me every two to four weeks but she did not interfere much in this first “stage”.\r\n<h2>Gaining momentum</h2>\r\nMid-November I started interviewing with a Fortune 100 Retail company and after two brief interviews, (with no prep - Elaine wanted me to be myself and didn''t provide any info!) Elaine told me I would be starting with them right away! I wanted to finalize my internship with my previous internship so I asked if I could work in both for one to two weeks. I also did that because my mentor at my previous internship was out of the office during that period and I was in charge. I owe a lot to her because she trusted me enough to be in charge during her absence.\r\n\r\nOnce I started at my new internship, everything changed! Here Elaine had given me amazing support and always wanted me to provide feedback and prep for my first meetings (coaching me with “fake meetings”).\r\n<h2>Like an internship, but better</h2>\r\nI was on-boarding for six weeks and started as an Iteration Manager. In the beginning, I was not confident and afraid I was not ready, but my mentor was always there to support me and remind me that they knew I was junior and an intern. I have just completed a month now and even though I know I’ve got a lot to learn I feel more confident. The support I''ve been getting from Avenue Code, and especially my mentor, still surprises me. I am not used to the concept of people investing in me simply because they believe in me. That is something I really love about Avenue Code, and my goal is to give back by being a great resource by help us win new clients and keeping the relationship strong with current ones.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Agile Cadet Program: A Firsthand Account', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'agile-cadet-program-a-firsthand-account', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:13:15', '2015-05-18 17:13:15', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=176', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(178, 1, '2015-05-12 19:41:34', '2015-05-12 19:41:34', '', 'Getting-startedwith-saucie-Cli', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'getting-startedwith-saucie-cli', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:41:34', '2015-05-12 19:41:34', '', 174, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Getting-startedwith-saucie-Cli.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(179, 1, '2015-05-12 19:41:40', '2015-05-12 19:41:40', 'You probably know that doing JavaScript testing is good, but one of the hurdles to overcome is how to test our code on different browsers. Luckily, there are some tools available for helping us overcome this hurdle. One of them is a CLI (<em>command line</em>) named <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://www.npmjs.com/package/saucie" rel="noreferrer"><em>saucie</em></a> developed by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/igorlima" rel="noreferrer">igorlima</a>. This CLI is a library hosted on <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://www.npmjs.com/" rel="noreferrer">NPM</a>, which allows you to integrate your frontend JavaScript tests with the <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/" rel="noreferrer">SauceLabs</a> platform. SauceLabs makes awesome cross browser testing, and <em>saucie</em> makes it easier to do cross browser testing by CLI.\r\n\r\nA great <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://tobyho.com/2012/06/24/testem-interactive-js-test-runner/" rel="noreferrer">interactive JS Test Runner</a>, the <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem" rel="noreferrer">testem</a> library, uses <em>saucie</em> on its <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem/tree/master/examples/saucelabs" rel="noreferrer">examples</a> and has the following <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://jasmine.github.io/" rel="noreferrer">jasmine</a> sample tests:\r\n\r\n<strong><em>hello.js</em></strong>\r\n<div class="highlight highlight-js">\r\n<pre><span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span> <span class="pl-en" style="color: #795da3;">hello</span>(<span class="pl-vpf">name</span>){\r\n    <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">return</span> “hello “ <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">+</span> (name <span class="pl-k" style="color: #a71d5d;">||</span> ‘world’);\r\n}</pre>\r\n</div>\r\n<strong><em>hello_spec.js</em></strong>\r\n<div class="highlight highlight-js">\r\n<pre>describe(‘hello’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n    it(‘should say hello’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n        expect(hello()).toBe(‘hello world’);\r\n    });\r\n    it(‘should say hello to person’, <span class="pl-st" style="color: #a71d5d;">function</span>(){\r\n        expect(hello(‘Bob’)).toBe(‘hello Bob’);\r\n    });\r\n});</pre>\r\n</div>\r\nRun these tests cross platforms step by step - you need only few command lines, as described below:\r\n<ol class="task-list">\r\n	<li>First of all <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/signup/trial" rel="noreferrer">create your SauceLabs account</a></li>\r\n	<li>Make sure the Sauce credentials are set as <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Environment_variable" rel="noreferrer">environment variables</a>:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><strong>SAUCE_USERNAME</strong> - your SauceLabs username</li>\r\n	<li><strong>SAUCE_ACCESS_KEY</strong> - your SauceLabs API/Access key.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>After that set up, follow the scripts below:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>npm install -g testem saucie</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>git clone git@github.com:airportyh/testem.git</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>cd testem/</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>git checkout tags/v0.7.1</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>cd examples/saucelabs/</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Keep that <strong>first</strong> terminal opened, open a <strong>second</strong> terminal, and follow the script below:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>cd testem/examples/saucelabs/</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>testem --port 8080</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n	<li>Go back to the <strong>first</strong> terminal and type:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="internet explorer" --versionSL="7.0" --platformSL="Windows XP"</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="iphone" --versionSL="8.1" --platformSL="OS X 10.10" --deviceNameSL="iPad Simulator" --deviceOrientationSL="portrait"</code></li>\r\n	<li><code>saucie --browserNameSL="android" --versionSL="4.1" --platformSL="Linux" --deviceNameSL="Motorola Atrix HD Emulator" --deviceOrientationSL="portrait"</code></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<strong>Note 1:</strong> <em>All platforms are listed <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/platforms/" rel="noreferrer">here</a>. Want to know the values for browserNameSL, versionSL and platformSL params? Check it <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://docs.saucelabs.com/reference/platforms-configurator/#/" rel="noreferrer">here</a></em>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 2:</strong> <em>If you’d like to use the default configuration just type <code>testem ci --port 8080</code> and be happy</em>.\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 3:</strong> <em>type <code>saucie --help</code> to get a help.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Note 4:</strong> <em>testem.yml is a <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/airportyh/testem#configuration-file" rel="noreferrer">configuration file</a> that specifies which JS framework to use. In this case, we are using JasmineJS.</em>\r\n\r\nDo you feel more comfortable watching a <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://showterm.io/592f4be927803a428035e" rel="noreferrer">video</a> instead? Go ahead and watch <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://showterm.io/592f4be927803a428035e" rel="noreferrer">it</a>.\r\n\r\nJust by typing a few command lines, everything was tested on cross browsers. Now let’s go to SauceLabs and check the result on many browsers, including the mobile ones such as iOS and Android:\r\n<ul class="task-list">\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/tests/06b62f4bba48469999d7212cf1b62818" rel="noreferrer">iOS test video</a></li>\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/tests/945ebbe3b6044963a017cef5949d1cf6" rel="noreferrer">IE7 test video</a></li>\r\n	<li><a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://saucelabs.com/jobs/11bd49cee6cf49d2a76d5b655f6ccb0f" rel="noreferrer">Android test video</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<em>Saucie </em>is still growing up and learning to integrate other platforms like <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="http://www.browserstack.com/" rel="noreferrer">BrowserStack</a>. New features are coming soon. And these days, it has<a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/igorlima/sauce-js-tests-integration/pull/4" rel="noreferrer"> some improvements</a> from <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach" rel="noreferrer">johanneswuerbach</a>. He made several changes <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach/ember-cli-sauce/commit/27036f2c97454abb5a2065fb5a754e7c972ddad4" rel="noreferrer">to use <em>saucie</em></a> in <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/johanneswuerbach/ember-cli-sauce" rel="noreferrer">ember-cli-sauce</a>, which is now used by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/tildeio/htmlbars" rel="noreferrer">htmlbars</a>, the rendering engine used by <a style="color: #4183c4;" href="https://github.com/emberjs/ember.js" rel="noreferrer">emberjs</a>.\r\n\r\nFeel free to file issue and send pull requests and let’s become <em>saucie</em> even better. Thanks!', 'Getting started with Saucie CLI', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '174-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:41:40', '2015-05-12 19:41:40', '', 174, 'http://localhost/acnew/174-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(180, 1, '2015-05-12 19:41:59', '2015-05-12 19:41:59', '', 'AE', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'ae', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:41:59', '2015-05-12 19:41:59', '', 175, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/AE.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0);
