(210, 1, '2014-10-29 21:47:34', '2014-10-29 21:47:34', '<p class="p1">This is part 2 of Object Oriented Programming: Modeling blog series. You can read part 1 <a href="http://avenuecode.com/object-oriented-programming-modelling-part-1/" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p class="p1"><strong>Modeling our problem!</strong></p>\r\nNow let’s try to model this using JAVA.  Eventually, we’re going to use code to construct the cube from scratch, but for now, we’re thinking through <em>how </em>we’re going to go about doing that.  What kind of things will we need to build a cube?  (Keep in mind that there are multiple ways to accomplish the same thing, and this is just one way, chosen for simplicity.)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe’ll start with the most basic building blocks: the colors themselves.  There are 6 colors that we need for the Rubik’s cube.  Also, these colors are all fixed, so we will use an <strong>ENUM </strong>to accomplish this:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.46.24-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-493 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.46.24-PM-300x57.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.46.24 PM" width="300" height="57" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhat else do we have on a cube?  Pieces!  As we saw earlier, centers, edges and corners will be different based on how many colors each one has, but all of them do have some distinct set of colors and some distinct position on the cube.  So let’s think of all the possible positions we can have.  We can also create an ENUM for it.  (We use ENUM, rather than just using the numbers, mainly to make the code easier to read.  Anytime you have a FIXED number of elements that have only one property (like colors, or positions), your best but is to create an ENUM for it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe java will look something like this:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.47.40-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-494" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.47.40-PM-1024x324.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.47.40 PM" width="600" height="190" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo far, we’ve defined colors and positions.\r\n\r\nNow let’s apply these two things--A position and a color/set of colors-- to define our Pieces.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.48.29-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-495" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.48.29-PM-300x119.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.48.29 PM" width="300" height="119" /></a>\r\n\r\nNow let’s make finer distinctions for our 3 types of pieces -- Edges, Corners and Centers.  Although these are different, these are all still pieces, needing a position and a color/set of colors.  So we can use inheritance, a nifty tool of OOP so that these 3 new classes will each be defined like our ‘Piece’ class.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-496" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.49.13-PM-300x79.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.49.13 PM" width="300" height="79" />\r\n\r\nNow let’s define our last class: The cube itself.\r\n\r\nAs we talked about before, a cube is a set of 26 pieces and some methods to modify it.  We will also need a way to check if the cube is solved -- which will involved using a boolean which will check if the cube is solved and then return either “true” or “false.”\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-497" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.50.50-PM-1024x515.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.50.50 PM" width="600" height="302" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Instantiating our objects</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOk, now we modelled our problem in an abstract sense, but now we need a “real cube.”\r\n\r\nWe refer to the process of creating CONCRETE objects as <strong>INSTANTIATION.  </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo instantiate a cube, we’ll need to start by instantiating its individual building blocks.  We need to instantiate each of its 26 distinct pieces.  Instantiating each piece involves 2 pieces of information, as we discussed earlier -- its position and its set of colors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo, using the class structure that we defined earlier, let’s instantiate a cube:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.52.31-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-498" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.52.31-PM-1024x116.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.52.31 PM" width="600" height="68" /></a>\r\n\r\nBut wait!  We modelled the position as a piece property, but we did more than we need to.  After all we don’t need to know where the piece will be placed on the cube in order to create it, right?  We can instead create a pile of individual pieces that we can put assemble later.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.57.36-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-499" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.57.36-PM-268x300.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.57.36 PM" width="268" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nSo let’s do a little change in our model:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.58.28-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-500" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.58.28-PM-300x180.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.58.28 PM" width="300" height="180" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMakes more sense, right?\r\n\r\nNotice that to do this we created a map.  A map associates is something we use to associate keys with values.  In this case, we are using the map to identify each piece with a particular spot on the cube.  Maps cannot contain duplicate keys, which is perfect for us since we cannot have more than one piece in each position in our cube.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo let’s try instantiating our cube again:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.11-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-501" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.11-PM-1024x310.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.59.11 PM" width="600" height="182" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAfter this, we will have something that looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.52-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-502" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.52-PM-288x300.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.59.52 PM" width="288" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow let’s add our edge pieces.\r\n\r\nFirst we instantiate the blue and yellow edge that will be our top front edge:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.00.48-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-503" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.00.48-PM-1024x82.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.00.48 PM" width="400" height="32" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.01.52-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-504" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.01.52-PM-150x150.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.01.52 PM" width="150" height="150" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNext, we place oru edge on the cube:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.15.57-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-506" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.15.57-PM-1024x75.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.15.57 PM" width="600" height="44" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHowever, we realize now that we are missing some crucial information: We don’t know which direction the piece is oriented.  It’s possible to place the cube so that it’s yellow side up, the correct way, but it can also be placed Blue up, incorrectly, as you can see:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.17.07-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-508" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.17.07-PM-150x150.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.17.07 PM" width="150" height="150" /></a> <a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.16.53-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-507" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.16.53-PM-150x150.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.16.53 PM" width="150" height="150" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo what can we do?  We didn’t account for this in our original plan… But we can fix the problem on the go.  Let’s add an Orientation property to our piece:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.18.01-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-509 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.18.01-PM-300x112.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.18.01 PM" width="300" height="112" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow we have all the information necessary to create a cube.  It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.19-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-510" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.19-PM-1024x194.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.19.19 PM" width="600" height="114" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.36-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-511" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.36-PM-1024x726.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.19.36 PM" width="600" height="426" /></a>\r\n\r\nCongratulations!  We’ve completed the first step: Creating an elegantly modeled cube!  Our next step will be to design the methods and functions so that we can modify the initial state of our cube.  We’ll tackle this in a future post, in which, among other things, I will unveil to you the entrancing beauty of TDD… But more on this later.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Object Oriented Programming: Modeling (part 2)', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'object-oriented-programming-modeling-part-2', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:22:35', '2015-05-18 17:22:35', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=210', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(211, 1, '2014-10-09 21:46:49', '2014-10-09 21:46:49', 'In Avenue Code, we do Agile.  Which means that we use post-its a lot.\r\n\r\nLike this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/1.png"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-470 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/1-300x300.png" alt="avenuecode" width="300" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nPost-its can be used to visually chart out your team’s progress in an easily manageable format.\r\n\r\nThey also moonlight as a valuable art medium!  Ranging from the kitsch to the classy, here are some of the most creative examples of post-it art we found online.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>1. A post-it paint job adds some retro flair to this Jaguar.</strong>\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="470"]<img src="http://www.shoplet.com/images/articles/post-it-jaguar.jpg" alt="avenuecode_best post it art" width="470" height="254" /> soure: http://www.shoplet.com/images/articles/post-it-jaguar.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n2. Who needs wallpaper?\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="500"]<img src="http://blog.catchmyparty.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/post-it-note-art.jpg" alt="avenuecode_best post it art" width="500" height="333" /> source: http://blog.catchmyparty.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/09/post-it-note-art.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n3. The best working enviroment\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="350"]<img src="http://www.examiner.com/images/blog/wysiwyg/image/post_it_stop_motion.jpg" alt="avenuecode post it art work" width="350" height="229" /> source:http://www.examiner.com/images/blog/wysiwyg/image/post_it_stop_motion.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n4. Video-game themes are ubiquitous\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="500"]<img src="http://www.geekosystem.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/post-it-note-bowser.jpeg" alt="avenuecode post it art" width="500" height="478" /> source: http://www.geekosystem.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/08/post-it-note-bowser.jpeg[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n5. Neon-colored post-its lend themselves to a psychedelic landscape\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="640"]<img src=" http://laughingsquid.com/wp-content/uploads/373e9c424adf56089c2537ff890a38dc.jpg" alt="avenuecode post it art" width="640" height="424" /> source: http://laughingsquid.com/wp-content/uploads/373e9c424adf56089c2537ff890a38dc.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n6. One more of that\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="750"]<img src="http://illusion.scene360.com/wp-content/themes/sahara-10/submissions/galeria_melissa_031.jpg" alt="avenuecode post it art" width="750" height="497" /> source: http://illusion.scene360.com/wp-content/themes/sahara-10/submissions/galeria_melissa_031.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n7. More video-game themes.\r\n\r\n<img src="http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-h9xfvObnjcg/URWoGPL1EBI/AAAAAAAAGXs/_bG5gUmr-ZU/s1600/D14660B4-D491-411C-8C5A-3EEF2B9662A3.JPG" alt="avenuecode post it art " width="1600" height="1200" /> source: http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-h9xfvObnjcg/URWoGPL1EBI/AAAAAAAAGXs/_bG5gUmr-ZU/s1600/D14660B4-D491-411C-8C5A-3EEF2B9662A3.JPG\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n8. Souled on this.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="350"]<img src="http://www.artnewsblog.com/images/post-it-notes.jpg" alt="avenue code post it art" width="350" height="277" /> source: http://www.artnewsblog.com/images/post-it-notes.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n9. Think outside the box\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="500"]<img src="http://blog.shoplet.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/rebecca-murtaugh-post-it-note-art.jpg" alt="" width="500" height="343" /> source: http://blog.shoplet.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/rebecca-murtaugh-post-it-note-art.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n10. Picking up on the craze, Marvel recently released pixel templates of its most popular pop-culture icons to the public.  Now you can adorn your space with your favorite hero in post-it form!\r\n\r\n[caption id="" align="aligncenter" width="576"]<img src="http://wac.450f.edgecastcdn.net/80450F/comicsalliance.com/files/2012/05/marvelpostits.jpg" alt="" width="576" height="263" /> source: http://wac.450f.edgecastcdn.net/80450F/comicsalliance.com/files/2012/05/marvelpostits.jpg[/caption]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '10 Great Post-it Art Pieces', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', '10-great-post-it-art-pieces', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:15:55', '2015-05-18 17:15:55', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=211', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(212, 1, '2014-09-24 21:45:00', '2014-09-24 21:45:00', 'This was a tasting menu kind of trip, a day or two in selected cities in Northern Europe. It was my first time, so I just wanted to feel the region in order to go back and spend more time on the favorite ones.\r\n\r\nPictures speak better than words, and one of my favorite pastime activities during travel is photography. So here is my trip in a picturesque and chronological order.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/01.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-416" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/01.png" alt="Copenhagen, DK" width="638" height="424" /></a>\r\n\r\nCopenhagen, DK. A little sleepy town, that comes to life only on Friday night between 6-7:30 pm. I wasn’t there to witness that crazy party. If you ever find yourself in there with nothing to do, ask for directions to Christiania Island, even for us non-smokers, this place is quite interesting to see. They don’t let you take pictures, so you’ll just have to see for yourself.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/02.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-417" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/02.png" alt="Viking Line crossing the Baltic from Stockholm to Helsinki" width="677" height="450" /></a>\r\n\r\nOn the Viking Line crossing the Baltic from Stockholm to Helsinki. This sky, beats the Da Vinci Sky in my opinion.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/03.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-418" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/03.png" alt="Silence Church in Helsinki" width="621" height="413" /></a>\r\n\r\nSilence Church in Helsinki. I think the design was inspired by a wine bottle’s cork. Helsinki reminded me of the eastern block, although they’ve never been a part of the Soviet Union, even with all the Russian arm-twisting. Go Fenland!! Your resilience can only be rivaled by you vodka.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/04.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-419" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/04.png" alt="04" width="638" height="424" /></a>\r\n\r\nOld Town Tallinn, Estonia.   I took this picture from a hang glider. No, seriously, have I ever exaggerated before?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/05.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-420" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/05.png" alt="05" width="597" height="750" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe Three Sisters Hotel in Old Tallinn, I had the room on the top left. This is the oldest building I’ve ever spent the night in, more than 700 years old.  Looking forward to breaking this record by sneaking a bed into the Pyramids.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/06.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-422" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/06.png" alt="Stockholm" width="898" height="597" /></a>\r\n\r\nGoodbye Nordic! last day, Stockholm.', 'My Trip to Northern Europe', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'my-trip-to-northern-europe', '', '', '2015-05-18 17:16:05', '2015-05-18 17:16:05', '', 0, 'http://localhost/acnew/?p=212', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(213, 1, '2015-05-12 19:57:18', '2015-05-12 19:57:18', '', 'unnamed', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'unnamed', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:57:18', '2015-05-12 19:57:18', '', 209, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/unnamed.png', 0, 'attachment', 'image/png', 0),
(214, 1, '2015-05-12 19:57:20', '2015-05-12 19:57:20', 'Now that this year is coming to fast close, it’s time to look ahead and prepare for how front-end design trends have grown and changed. We talked to our talented team of engineers and asked them what they believe their top front-end developer trends are for 2015.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2><b>Compatibility </b></h2>\r\n<h3><i>AngularJS, BackboneJS, React are still going strong.</i></h3>\r\nJavascript frameworks - such as <b>AngularJS, Backbone.js </b>and <b>React </b>- have reached a new stability level,  and cross-browser compatibility has developed in such a way that it''s no longer a risk to implement JS based applications. Before, cross-browser compatibility used to prevent big corporations from adopting those frameworks, as they usually had to support a lot of old browsers. Nowadays, frameworks have better support for multiple browsers (and most of them are still supporting really old ones like IE7, IE8). As a result, they are being used more by big players in the market. That''s a trend we can see with most of our clients at Avenue Code.\r\n<h2><b>Web Components</b></h2>\r\n<h3><i>libraries agree - components are awesome!</i></h3>\r\nWeb Components will become even more important in 2015 because it will turn front-end development inside out. Web Components greatly simplifies how UI components are developed, by favoring reuse and sharing component-specific knowledge. It will trend because of the increasing focus on the "web componentizing" approach advocated by libraries such as <b>React</b>, which forces the developer to define the web application as a tree of fully-featured components. Besides that, there has been a big progress leap with the specification of Web Components, which is being widely promoted by libraries such as <b>Polymer </b>and <b>X-Tags</b>.\r\n\r\nWeb Components are awesome because it directly attacks the current number of development challenges - such as code repetition, bad cohesion, poor coupling, inability to reuse the component in different contexts, and lack of testing and certification by the community, which essentially forces one to reinvent the wheel each time. Web Components will provide a productivity boom for the front-end development world.\r\n<h2><b><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Mobile-1.png">\r\n</a><a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Mobile-1.png"><img class="alignleft wp-image-562 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Mobile-1-212x300.png" alt="" width="212" height="300" /></a></b><b></b></h2>\r\n<h2><b>Mobile-first Design</b></h2>\r\n<h3><i>Consumers can be found on their phones, we must adjust accordingly!</i></h3>\r\nMobile-first design should lead development methods due to responsive design techniques maturedness. Mobile device usage has exploded, and creative teams should explore newer features (e.g. geolocation, touch) in order to define unique experiences like real-time trackers, local-based content, etc.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h2><b><img class="alignleft wp-image-563 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Untitled-design-200x300.png" alt="Untitled design" width="200" height="300" />User Experience</b></h2>\r\n<h3><i>Natural design will still be king.</i></h3>\r\nNext year’s UX trends will take advantage of some natural (intuitive) gestures provided by the mobile devices themselves (especially swiping and scrolling). As a direct result, there should be more usage of content in a single page instead of the user having to click on multiple links to find what he or she is looking for.\r\n\r\nThe cool thing about these three trends is that they converge to provide a faster, more intuitive, and cleaner web experience that stays consistent regardless of when a user switches from one device to another. Lastly, community will continue to be a large part of front-end design, specifically with web components.\r\nLooks like the theme for 2015 is beautifully simple and stable front-end design and development. We aim to do more with less...looks like everyone else will too in the new year.', 'Front-end Design Trends for 2015', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '209-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:57:20', '2015-05-12 19:57:20', '', 209, 'http://localhost/acnew/209-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(215, 1, '2015-05-12 19:57:31', '2015-05-12 19:57:31', '', 'rubikscube_tissuebox_web', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', 'rubikscube_tissuebox_web', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:57:31', '2015-05-12 19:57:31', '', 210, 'http://localhost/acnew/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/rubikscube_tissuebox_web.jpg', 0, 'attachment', 'image/jpeg', 0),
(216, 1, '2015-05-12 19:57:34', '2015-05-12 19:57:34', '<p class="p1">This is part 2 of Object Oriented Programming: Modeling blog series. You can read part 1 <a href="http://avenuecode.com/object-oriented-programming-modelling-part-1/" target="_blank">here</a>.</p>\r\n<p class="p1"><strong>Modeling our problem!</strong></p>\r\nNow let’s try to model this using JAVA.  Eventually, we’re going to use code to construct the cube from scratch, but for now, we’re thinking through <em>how </em>we’re going to go about doing that.  What kind of things will we need to build a cube?  (Keep in mind that there are multiple ways to accomplish the same thing, and this is just one way, chosen for simplicity.)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWe’ll start with the most basic building blocks: the colors themselves.  There are 6 colors that we need for the Rubik’s cube.  Also, these colors are all fixed, so we will use an <strong>ENUM </strong>to accomplish this:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.46.24-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-493 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.46.24-PM-300x57.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.46.24 PM" width="300" height="57" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhat else do we have on a cube?  Pieces!  As we saw earlier, centers, edges and corners will be different based on how many colors each one has, but all of them do have some distinct set of colors and some distinct position on the cube.  So let’s think of all the possible positions we can have.  We can also create an ENUM for it.  (We use ENUM, rather than just using the numbers, mainly to make the code easier to read.  Anytime you have a FIXED number of elements that have only one property (like colors, or positions), your best but is to create an ENUM for it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe java will look something like this:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.47.40-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-494" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.47.40-PM-1024x324.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.47.40 PM" width="600" height="190" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo far, we’ve defined colors and positions.\r\n\r\nNow let’s apply these two things--A position and a color/set of colors-- to define our Pieces.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.48.29-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-495" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.48.29-PM-300x119.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.48.29 PM" width="300" height="119" /></a>\r\n\r\nNow let’s make finer distinctions for our 3 types of pieces -- Edges, Corners and Centers.  Although these are different, these are all still pieces, needing a position and a color/set of colors.  So we can use inheritance, a nifty tool of OOP so that these 3 new classes will each be defined like our ‘Piece’ class.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-496" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.49.13-PM-300x79.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.49.13 PM" width="300" height="79" />\r\n\r\nNow let’s define our last class: The cube itself.\r\n\r\nAs we talked about before, a cube is a set of 26 pieces and some methods to modify it.  We will also need a way to check if the cube is solved -- which will involved using a boolean which will check if the cube is solved and then return either “true” or “false.”\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-497" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.50.50-PM-1024x515.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.50.50 PM" width="600" height="302" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Instantiating our objects</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nOk, now we modelled our problem in an abstract sense, but now we need a “real cube.”\r\n\r\nWe refer to the process of creating CONCRETE objects as <strong>INSTANTIATION.  </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTo instantiate a cube, we’ll need to start by instantiating its individual building blocks.  We need to instantiate each of its 26 distinct pieces.  Instantiating each piece involves 2 pieces of information, as we discussed earlier -- its position and its set of colors.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo, using the class structure that we defined earlier, let’s instantiate a cube:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.52.31-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-498" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.52.31-PM-1024x116.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.52.31 PM" width="600" height="68" /></a>\r\n\r\nBut wait!  We modelled the position as a piece property, but we did more than we need to.  After all we don’t need to know where the piece will be placed on the cube in order to create it, right?  We can instead create a pile of individual pieces that we can put assemble later.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.57.36-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-499" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.57.36-PM-268x300.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.57.36 PM" width="268" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\nSo let’s do a little change in our model:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.58.28-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-500" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.58.28-PM-300x180.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.58.28 PM" width="300" height="180" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMakes more sense, right?\r\n\r\nNotice that to do this we created a map.  A map associates is something we use to associate keys with values.  In this case, we are using the map to identify each piece with a particular spot on the cube.  Maps cannot contain duplicate keys, which is perfect for us since we cannot have more than one piece in each position in our cube.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo let’s try instantiating our cube again:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.11-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-501" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.11-PM-1024x310.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.59.11 PM" width="600" height="182" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAfter this, we will have something that looks like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.52-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-502" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-2.59.52-PM-288x300.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 2.59.52 PM" width="288" height="300" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow let’s add our edge pieces.\r\n\r\nFirst we instantiate the blue and yellow edge that will be our top front edge:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.00.48-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-503" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.00.48-PM-1024x82.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.00.48 PM" width="400" height="32" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.01.52-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-504" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.01.52-PM-150x150.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.01.52 PM" width="150" height="150" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNext, we place oru edge on the cube:\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.15.57-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-506" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.15.57-PM-1024x75.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.15.57 PM" width="600" height="44" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHowever, we realize now that we are missing some crucial information: We don’t know which direction the piece is oriented.  It’s possible to place the cube so that it’s yellow side up, the correct way, but it can also be placed Blue up, incorrectly, as you can see:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.17.07-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-508" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.17.07-PM-150x150.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.17.07 PM" width="150" height="150" /></a> <a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.16.53-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-thumbnail wp-image-507" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.16.53-PM-150x150.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.16.53 PM" width="150" height="150" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nSo what can we do?  We didn’t account for this in our original plan… But we can fix the problem on the go.  Let’s add an Orientation property to our piece:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.18.01-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-509 size-medium" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.18.01-PM-300x112.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.18.01 PM" width="300" height="112" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNow we have all the information necessary to create a cube.  It will look something like this:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.19-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-510" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.19-PM-1024x194.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.19.19 PM" width="600" height="114" /></a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.36-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-511" src="http://avenuecode.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Screen-Shot-2014-10-28-at-3.19.36-PM-1024x726.png" alt="Screen Shot 2014-10-28 at 3.19.36 PM" width="600" height="426" /></a>\r\n\r\nCongratulations!  We’ve completed the first step: Creating an elegantly modeled cube!  Our next step will be to design the methods and functions so that we can modify the initial state of our cube.  We’ll tackle this in a future post, in which, among other things, I will unveil to you the entrancing beauty of TDD… But more on this later.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Object Oriented Programming: Modeling (part 2)', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '210-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-12 19:57:34', '2015-05-12 19:57:34', '', 210, 'http://localhost/acnew/210-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
